What Is Artificial Intelligence?
At its core, AI is the simulation of human intelligence in machines — building systems that can learn from experience, reason about problems, and adapt to new situations.
A useful analogy: imagine you've been asked to learn and explain a topic you've never studied before — say, aerospace engineering. You'd read books, search for articles, synthesize notes, and then explain the concept in your own words. You wouldn't copy-paste; you'd genuinely generate an understanding. That's what AI aims to replicate.

Traditional AI vs. Generative AI
This distinction is critical to understand, especially for career positioning.
Traditional AI (pre-2022 mainstream)

Task-specific: one model per problem (spam detection, churn prediction, fraud detection)
Required labeled data and programming skills (Python, R)
Output: predictions and classifications — it analyzed data but didn't create anything new
Example: A model trained to predict whether a bank transaction is fraudulent, based on historical patterns

Generative AI (post-2022 mainstream)

Multi-purpose: a single model can translate, summarize, write code, draft emails, and more
Accessible through natural language — no coding required for most tasks
Output: new, original content — text, images, code, audio, video
Example: Asking ChatGPT to draft a business proposal, then asking it to summarize the same document, then translate it — all in one session

The shift from Traditional to Generative AI is what made prompt engineering the new power skill. You no longer need to code a model; you need to know how to communicate with one.

How the Brain Inspired Neural Networks
The human brain has roughly 100 billion neurons. Each neuron receives signals through its dendrites, processes them in its nucleus, and sends output down its axon to the next neuron. Connections strengthen or weaken based on experience — that's how learning happens.
Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) mirror this structure:

Input layer — receives raw data (pixels, words, numbers)
Hidden layers — transform the data through weighted calculations
Output layer — produces a result (a classification, a word, a prediction)

The more hidden layers a network has, the "deeper" it is — hence the term Deep Learning. Deep networks can model complex, non-linear patterns in data that shallow networks miss.

Key stat: GPT-3, the model behind early ChatGPT, has 175 billion parameters (the adjustable weights across connections). That exceeds the estimated 100 billion neurons in a human brain — though the comparison isn't perfectly apples-to-apples.

Real-world example — Tesla Autopilot:
Camera input → Deep neural network → Identifies lanes, pedestrians, traffic signs → Calculates steering, braking, acceleration decisions — all within milliseconds.

How AI Learns: Three Training Paradigms
Understanding how models are trained helps you use them more intelligently.
1. Supervised Learning
The model is trained on labeled examples — input paired with the correct answer. Like a student studying with an answer key.

Use case: Spam filters, sentiment analysis, medical image diagnosis
Challenge: Expensive and slow — requires humans to label thousands or millions of examples

2. Unsupervised Learning
The model finds patterns in unlabeled data without being told what to look for.

Use case: Customer segmentation (grouping shoppers by behaviour, without pre-defined categories), anomaly detection
Think: Sorting a mixed bag of items by similarity without knowing their names first

3. Self-Supervised Learning
The model generates its own labels from raw data. This is how LLMs are pre-trained.

Use case: The model reads the internet and learns to predict the next word in every sentence. The surrounding text is the label.
Why it matters: It allows training on virtually unlimited data without human annotation — enabling the scale that makes models like GPT possible.


Generative Models — How AI Creates
The question many people ask: is AI just copy-pasting from its training data? The answer is no.
Generative models learn the underlying patterns of data, not specific examples. Once trained, they can produce entirely new outputs that fit those patterns.
Analogy: Show a child hundreds of photos of animals. After a while, ask the child to draw an animal they've never seen. They'll draw something plausible — four legs, fur, eyes — because they've internalized the rules, not the images.
AI does the same. An image generator that's never seen "an astronaut riding a horse on the moon" can generate that image because it separately learned what astronauts look like, what horses look like, and what the moon looks like.
Two key generative architectures before Transformers:
GANs (Generative Adversarial Networks)
Two neural networks in competition:

The Generator produces fake samples (images, audio, etc.)
The Discriminator tries to tell the fake from the real
They train together — each improves by trying to outsmart the other
Result: Increasingly photorealistic outputs
Famous example: thispersondoesnotexist.com — every face is AI-generated from scratch

VAEs (Variational Autoencoders)

The Encoder compresses an input (e.g. an image) into a compact representation
The Decoder reconstructs the image from that compressed form
Key use: Image compression — reducing a 2MB photo to 80KB without visibly degrading quality
Also used in anomaly detection and drug discovery


Transformers — The Architecture Behind Modern AI
The 2017 Google paper "Attention Is All You Need" changed everything. It introduced the Transformer architecture, which underpins virtually every major LLM today: ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Llama, and more.
What made Transformers different:

Older models (RNNs) processed text sequentially — one word at a time, left to right
Transformers process the entire input simultaneously, making them dramatically faster and better at capturing long-range relationships

How a Transformer processes a sentence:

Tokenization — Text is split into tokens (words or sub-words), each mapped to a number. "Attention is powerful" might become [7823, 318, 4007] — this is what the model actually sees.
Embeddings — Each token number is converted to a vector (a list of hundreds of floating-point values) that encodes meaning. Similar words have similar vectors — "cat" and "kitten" are closer together than "cat" and "spreadsheet".
Positional Encoding — Since order matters in language, a positional signal is added to each embedding so the model knows "this word came third in the sentence."
Encoder (attention + feed-forward) — The self-attention mechanism lets each word "look at" every other word to understand context. In "The trophy didn't fit in the suitcase because it was too big," attention helps the model figure out that "it" refers to the trophy, not the suitcase.
Decoder — Generates the output one token at a time, using the encoded context. Each predicted token feeds back into the next prediction — that's why responses appear word-by-word.


Understanding LLMs
LLMs (Large Language Models) are a specific category within Generative AI — focused on text understanding and generation.
At their core, LLMs do one thing: predict the next most likely token given everything that came before. This sounds simple, but when done at scale across billions of parameters trained on virtually the entire internet, it produces something that can explain quantum physics, write Python scripts, and debate philosophy.
Types of LLMs:
TypeDescriptionExampleGeneric/Base ModelPre-trained on raw text; can't be chatted with directlyGPT-2, early BERTInstruction-TunedFine-tuned to follow specific instructionsLlama-3-InstructDialogue-TunedFine-tuned for natural conversationChatGPT, Claude, Gemini
Why don't LLMs always give the same answer?
By design. LLMs sample from a probability distribution rather than always choosing the single most likely word. This is controlled by a temperature setting — lower temperature makes responses more deterministic and factual; higher temperature makes them more creative and varied.

